Introduction¶

  • This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan form Prosper, an online peer-to-peer lending marketplace based in the United States.
  • This data is contained in a csv file downloadable from a udacity-hosted page.

  1. The following variables have many missing values: TotalProsperLoans, TotalProsperPaymentsBilled, OnTimeProsperPayments, ProsperPaymentsLessThanOneMonthLate, ProsperPaymentsOneMonthPlusLate, ProsperPrincipalBorrowed, ProsperPrincipalOutstanding, ScorexChangeAtTimeOfListing, and LoanFirstDefaultedCycleNumber.

  2. Becaause of the sheer number of variables and time constraints, I intend to explore relationships and trends only among a limited number of variables (about 20).

  3. These include: ListingNumber, ListingCreationDate, Term, LoanStatus, BorrowerState, Occupation, EmploymentStatus, EmploymentStatusDuration, IsBorrowerHomeowner, DebtToIncomeRatio, IncomeRange, IncomeVerifiable, StatedMonthlyIncome, BorrowerAPR, BorrowerRate, [CreditGrade, ProsperRating (numeric), ProsperRating (Alpha)], LenderYield, ListingCategory, Investors, InvestmentFromFriendsAmount, InvestmentFromFriendsCount

  • The variables in square brackets all represent the same quantity.

Some Quality and Tidiness Issues:

  • ListingCreationDate is not in DateTime format.
  • The columns CreditGrade, ProsperRating (numeric), and ProsperRating (Alpha) represent almost the same quantity.
  • Column name ListingCategory (numeric) is cumbersome. It should be an ordered categorical variable.
  • Convert nan values in EmploymentStatus to 'Other'.
  • Columns LoanStatus, BorrowerState, Occupation, and EmploymentStatus should also be categorical variables. However, only LoanStatus and EmploymentStatus should be converted with time constraints in mind.

#create function to set values
def setRating(rating_val):
    if not pd.isna(rating_val):        
        return rating_val
    else:
        return ''

# Convert nan values in `EmploymentStatus` to 'Other'.

#use custom helper function
def convertNaN(val):
    '''Helper function to convert EmploymentStatus value nan to 'Not available' 
        val: any value of this series '''
    if pd.isna(val):
        return 'Not available'
    else:
        return val
    
loan_df_subset_copy['EmploymentStatus'] = loan_df_subset_copy['EmploymentStatus'].apply(lambda x: convertNaN(x))

What is the structure of the dataset?¶

The dataset has one hundred and thirteen thousand, nine hundred and thirty seven observations with 81 variables each.

The smaller, somewhat cleaned dataset has only 21 variables, 3 of which will be merged into one, thus leaving it with just 19 variables

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The dataset contains the loan data of over 100,000 clients of Prosper Loans. It contains vital information on their identity, credit rating, social status, the type and duration of loans they applied for, and the status of their loan. It also contains information on the status of previous loans, and how many people have invested in their loans.

Other important features include their employment status, occupation, salary, and Borrower state.

I am most interested in how these variables influenced investor behaviour and client ability to secure and to pay off their loans.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • I have divided the features (variables) into three broad categories:
1. Features that describe the social status of the borrower such as: Occupation, EmploymentStatus, EmploymentStatusDuration, IsBorrowerHomeowner, DebtToIncomeRatio, IncomeRange, IncomeVerifiable, and StatedMonthlyIncome.


2. Features that describe the client and may imply his or her character, such as: CreditGrade, ProsperRating (numeric), and ProsperRating (Alpha). Others might include: 'InvestmentFromFriendsCount', 'InvestmentFromFriendsAmount', and 'Investors'.


3. Loan-specific features and how they might affect client ability to pay. These include: ListingNumber, ListingCreationDate, Term, BorrowerAPR, and BorrowerRate.

  • I expect that for clients with a higher social status, e.g a client that is employed, a home owner, with a higher income range would have a positive loan status (that is, has payed off his or her loan)

  • In addition, I expect that clients with a higher credit rating would have greater number of investors and a favorable loan status.

  • Lastly, I expect that loans with a shorter term, higher BorrowerAPR and Borrower rate would be more likely to have a negative loan status.

#write a function to make countplot

def make_countplot(x, dataset=loan_df_subset_copy):
    ''' Create Plot function to make count barplots for subcategories of some categorical variables
        x: Categorical variable of Interest
        dataset: any dataset, but default is loan_df_subset_copy 
        The function supports value-annotated bars '''
    categories = dataset[x].value_counts().index
    values = dataset[x].value_counts().values
    categoryname = '{val_x}'.format(val_x=x)
    newdict = {categoryname:categories,
              'Counts': values}   
    columns = [categoryname, 'Counts']  
    plot_order = categories
    count_dataframe = pd.DataFrame(newdict, columns=columns)
    plt.xticks(rotation=65)
    color_index = randrange(10)
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[color_index]
    ax = sb.barplot(data=count_dataframe, x=columns[0], y=columns[1], color = default_color, order=plot_order);
    plt.title("Subcategories of {categoryname} by Counts".format(categoryname=columns[0]))
    i = 0
    for p in ax.patches:
        count = '{f}'.format(f=count_dataframe[columns[1]][i])
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() - 0.25
        y= p.get_height() + 1.25
        ax.annotate(count, (x, y), ha='center')
        i = i + 1


#write a function to create a percentage dataset
def makePercentTable(x, dataset=loan_df_subset_copy):
    ''' Create  function to make Percentage tables for subcategories of some categorical variables
        x: Categorical variable of Interest
        dataset: any dataset, but default is loan_df_subset_copy 
        The function returns a dataframe'''
    categories = dataset[x].value_counts().index
    values = dataset[x].value_counts().values
    total = dataset[x].count()
    index = 0
    indices= []
    percentages = []
    categoryname = '{val_x}'.format(val_x=x)
    for category in categories:
        categorypercent  = round((values[index]/total) * 100, 1)
        percentages.append(categorypercent)
        indices.append(index)
        index = index + 1
    newObjdict = {categoryname:categories,
              'Percentage(%)': percentages}   
    columns = [categoryname, 'Percentage(%)']    
    mydataframe = pd.DataFrame(newObjdict, columns=columns, index=indices)
    return mydataframe
        
##write a function to create a percentage barplot    
def percentplot(dataset):
    ''' Create Plot function to make Percentage barplots for subcategories of some categorical variables
        dataset: any count dataframe, but supports returned dataframes from function `makePercentTable`  
        The function supports value-annotated bars '''
    columns = dataset.columns.tolist()
    dataset.sort_values(by=[columns[1]], ascending=False, inplace=True)
    plot_order = dataset[columns[0]].tolist()
    #plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
    plt.ylim(0,100)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    color_index = randrange(10)
    total = float(len(dataset))
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[color_index]
    ax = sb.barplot(data=dataset, x=columns[0], y=columns[1], color = default_color, order=plot_order);
    plt.title("Categories of {categoryname} by Percentage".format(categoryname=columns[0]))
    i = 0
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(dataset[columns[1]][i])
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() - 0.25
        y= p.get_height() + 1
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), ha='center')
        i = i + 1

def linear_histogram(x,xlabel,binsize,dataset=loan_df_subset_copy):
    ''' Create Plot function to make histogram charts for numeric variables using a linear xscale
        x: Numeric variable of Interest
        dataset: any dataset, but default is loan_df_subset_copy 
        binsize(int): any suitable binsize
        The function creates suitably-annotated plots '''
    binsize = binsize
    bins = np.arange(0, dataset[x].max() + binsize, binsize)
    
    colors1 = sb.color_palette("rocket")
    color1= colors1[randrange(len(colors1))]
    color = colors[randrange(len(colors))]
    plt.ylabel('Number of Loans')
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.title("Distribution of {categoryname} by Count".format(categoryname=x))
    plt.hist(data=dataset, x=x, color=color1, bins=bins)

def log10_histogram(x,xlabel,binsize,dataset=loan_df_subset_copy):
    ''' Create Plot function to make histogram charts for numeric variables using a log 10 xscale
        x: Numeric variable of Interest
        dataset: any dataset, but default is loan_df_subset_copy 
        binsize(float): any suitable binsize
        The function creates suitably-annotated plots '''
    binsize = binsize
    bins = 10 ** np.arange(np.log10(dataset[x].min()+ 1), np.log10(dataset[x].max() + binsize), np.log10(binsize))
    
    colors1 = sb.color_palette("rocket")
    color1= colors1[randrange(len(colors1))]
    color = colors[randrange(len(colors))]
    plt.ylabel('Number of Loans')
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.title("Distribution of {categoryname} by Count".format(categoryname=x))
    plt.hist(data=dataset, x=x, color=color1, bins=bins)
    plt.xscale('log')

#lets create some functions again

def meanCount_table(x, var_2,dataset=loan_df_subset_copy):
    ''' Create  function to make Average tables for subcategories of a categorical variable
        x: categorical variable to group by
        var2: numeric variable for mean calculation
        dataset: any dataset, but default is loan_df_subset_copy 
        The function returns a dataframe '''
    # x -categorical variable to group by
    # var2 - numeric variable for mean calculation
    categories = dataset.groupby(x).mean().index.tolist()
    counts = dataset[x].value_counts().values
    avg_var = dataset.groupby(x).mean()[var_2].tolist()
    categoryname = '{val_x}'.format(val_x=x)
    avg_var2 = 'Mean_{v_mean}'.format(v_mean=var_2, cat=categoryname)
    newdict = {
               categoryname:categories,
              'Counts': counts,
               avg_var2: avg_var
              }   
    columns = [categoryname, 'Counts', avg_var2]  
    count_dataframe = pd.DataFrame(newdict, columns=columns)
    return count_dataframe

def my_barplot(dataset, x, y, title='', colorindex=0):
    ''' Create Plot function to make barplots for mean values of the subcategories of a categorical variable
        dataset: any grouped 'average' dataframe with averages of a numeric variable by subcategories of a categorical variable,
        but supports returned dataframes from function `meanCount_table`  
        colorindex: any integer less than 20, gives us the freedom to select from a range of colors. 
        The function supports basic annotations '''
    colors = sb.color_palette('Paired')
    color = colors[colorindex]
    plt.title(title)
    sb.barplot(data=dataset, y=y, x=x, color=color)

Conclusions¶

  1. Over 80% of all Prosper Loans debtors are earning or earned more than $25,000 per year. In the same vein, over 80% of this same population were or are employed in some way. It would seem that Prosper Loan investors were more likely to lend to creditors that are or were in some form of employment.

  2. The majority of Prosper Loans -56,576 loans are current loans. This represents 49.7% of all their loans. A close second subcategory of Prosper loans have been completely repaid (38,074), which represents 33.4% of all their loans. Together with the current loans, they both make up 83.1% of all Prosper loans. A distant third subcategory of loans have been charged off (written off as losses) - a whopping 10.5%. This is apart from the 4.4% of loans that have been defaulted on.

  3. Prosper Loan Borrowers generally have or had a high credit rating, that is those with 5 and above accounted for more than half of all loans (58.1%). Those with a median credit rating (4/7) had 21.1% of all recorded loans, which is the highest of any individual credit rating.

  4. Home ownership seems to play less of a role in influencing which borrowers get loans, although Homeowners were slightly more than non homeowners.

  5. Prosper loans are quite profitable, with most of them having a profitabilty of between 10% and 25%.

  6. Connecticut, Washington DC and New Jersey have the highest monthly incomes, while indiana, Maine and North Dakota are in the bottom 3. Utah, Massassuchets and Wyoming have the highest debt to income ratio, while New York, New Jersey and Washington DC have the lowest 3 values in that order. However, the top 3 states by average mean lender yield were Alabama, North Dakota and Indiana. The bottom 3 were Washington DC, Maine and Indiana.

  7. Except for zero credit rating, the borrower rates, borrower APR and lender yields fell progressively with increasing credit ratings while investor numbers increased progressively with higher credit ratings. Could this be explained by highly rated borrowers negotiating lower rates for themselves because investors prefer security to risk?

  8. Debt to Income Ratio, Employment Status duration and Stated Monthly income remained at relatively stable levels accross all the credit grades.

  9. People on full time jobs attracted the highest investor numbers and some of the lower interest loans. Unemployed folks had a staggeringly high debt to income ratios compared to other employment categories.

  10. The completed loans had some of the lowest lender yields, comparable to current loans. Completed loans had some of the lowest rates, also comparable to current loans. These other 'bad' loans have higher interest rates.

  11. Loans to Home owners had better yields across the credit categories compared to non-home owners, and investors preferred medium term loans the most, followed by longer term loans. They funded shorter term loans the least.
